Pattern used in Ferguson:
    from external channel -> put message in REST API , 
    API will save the collection as received collection (rcvd) and publish message in metdata format (id and eventdata) to topic ,
    topic will be subscribed by multiple queue. 
    writer service will subscribe the message from corresponding queue and fetch the data from received collection based on metadata
    and  write the message in collection data model (CDM) . 
    update , add , delete will be determined as type in message which is published to topic ,
    sync id will be there , if its latest than existing then update the data .
    if any failure occurs goes for retry .If successful save in CDM collections .
    And there is a redeliver rest service ,  In redeliver it will try to put again on queue similar to publisher based on Id and data range. 
    if again fails moves to DLQ. 

1. The Ingestion Flow:
External Channel → REST API: 
      The raw payload is persisted immediately into a Received Collection. 
      This acts as your "Source of Truth" or an audit log of exactly what was sent.
Metadata Publisher: The API publishes a slim message to a Topic.
      Payload: { "id": "123", "eventData": "...", "type": "UPDATE/ADD/DELETE", "syncId": 20260331 }
Fan-out: The Topic pushes this metadata to multiple Subscriber Queues.
2. The Writer Service Logic:
The Writer Service is the "brain" of the operation. It performs the following steps:
Hydration: It receives the metadata, then fetches the full document from the Received Collection using the id.
Idempotency & Versioning: It compares the syncId from the message against the syncId already in the CDM.
          If $syncId_{new} > syncId_{existing}$, the operation proceeds
          If it's older, the message is discarded to prevent "stale" data from overwriting newer updates (a common issue in asynchronous systems).
Transformation: It maps the raw data into the CDM schema based on the type (Add, Update, or Delete).
     When performing a DELETE based on a syncId, consider using Soft Deletes (a deleted: true flag). 
3. Error Handling & Redelivery
Scenario             Action
First Failure        The message enters a Retry Loop (exponential backoff is usually best here).
Exhausted Retries    The message is sent to a Dead Letter Queue (DLQ) or flagged for the Redeliver Service.
Redeliver Service    A manual or scheduled REST trigger that fetches original data by ID or Date Range and re-injects it into the flow.

Yes, it ensures Eventual Consistency.
Safety: No matter what order messages arrive in (Update 2 before Update 1), 
        the database will always end up with the state of the message that has the highest timestamp.
Liveness: Your Redeliver Service can safely re-send old data from the "Received Collection" without fear of corrupting the CDM,
          because the long timestamp check will automatically ignore the re-delivered "old" data if the CDM is already more current.
Verdict: A long timestamp is excellent for 95% of use cases. 
        As long as you generate the timestamp at the entry point and use a "Strictly Greater Than" check in your Writer, your data consistency will be solid.


AKS Strageies:
Deploying and managing applications on Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) requires a strategy that balances cost, reliability, and speed.
Because AKS is a managed service, your focus shifts from managing the "Master Node" to optimizing your Worker Nodes and Traffic Flow.

AKS Cluster Architecture Strategies
    A. The Networking Strategy (CNI vs. Kubenet)
        Choosing your network plugin is the most important "Day 1" decision because it’s hard to change later.
        Azure CNI (Advanced): Every Pod gets a real IP from your Azure Virtual Network.
                    Best for: Large enterprises needing direct connectivity to Pods from On-Premise.
        Kubenet (Basic): Only Nodes get VNet IPs; Pods get internal IPs.
                    Best for: Saving IP addresses if your VNet range is small.
    B. Node Pool Strategy
    Don't put everything in one bucket. Use multiple Node Pools:
            System Pool: Runs critical K8s services (CoreDNS, Metrics). Keep this small and stable.
            User Pool: Runs your actual apps. Use Spot Instances here for non-critical dev/test workloads to save up to 90% on costs.
            GPU Pool: Dedicated pools for AI/ML tasks using N-Series VMs.

Automation: GitOps vs. Push
In AKS, you should avoid kubectl apply from your laptop.
Push Strategy (Azure DevOps/GitHub Actions): Your CI/CD pipeline logs into the cluster and "pushes" the YAML.
GitOps Strategy (Flux or ArgoCD): You install an agent inside AKS. 
        It watches your Git repo. If you change a file in Git, the agent "pulls" the change into the cluster.
    Why: This is the "self-healing" method. 
        If someone manually deletes a Pod, the GitOps agent will recreate it to match Git.

Scaling Strategy:
   AKS offers three layers of scaling that must work together:
        HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler): Adds more Pods if CPU/RAM is high.
        Cluster Autoscaler: Adds more VM Nodes if there is no room for the new Pods.
        VPA (Vertical Pod Autoscaler): Automatically adjusts the CPU/RAM limits of your pods if they are under-provisioned.

Deployment rollback Strategy:
    A Deployment Rollback Strategy is the plan for how you revert your production environment to a previous stable state
    when a new release fails health checks, shows bugs, or degrades performance.
    In modern DevOps, "rolling back" isn't just about clicking an undo button; 
    it’s about how you manage traffic and infrastructure to minimize the "blast radius" of a failure.

1. Blue-Green Deployment (The "Mirror" Strategy)
    This is the cleanest and fastest rollback method. 
    You maintain two identical production environments.
        How it works: "Blue" is the current live version. You deploy the new code to "Green." 
                     Once Green is ready, you flip the Load Balancer or Route 53 settings to point to Green.
        The Rollback: If Green starts throwing errors, you simply flip the switch back to Blue.
        Benefit: Immediate recovery.
        Risk: Costly, as you need double the infrastructure.
2. Canary Deployment (The "Testing in Production" Strategy)
    Instead of switching everyone at once, you roll out the new version to a small subset of users (e.g., 5%).
        How it works: You monitor the 5% for "Golden Signals" (Latency, Errors, Traffic, Saturation). 
                     If they look good, you increase to 25%, 50%, then 100%.
        The Rollback: If the 5% experience issues, you simply kill the canary instances. 
                    The other 95% of users were never affected.
        Benefit: Extremely low blast radius.
3. Rolling Updates (The "One-by-One" Strategy)
    Common in Kubernetes, this replaces old instances with new ones gradually.
        How it works: If you have 10 servers, the system kills 1 old server and starts 1 new one until the transition is complete.
        The Rollback: If the new servers fail health checks,
                     the orchestrator stops the update and begins a "Reverse Rolling Update" to bring back the old versions.
        Risk: During the update, your users are hitting two different versions of the app simultaneously.
4. Feature Toggles (The "Logic" Rollback)
    Sometimes the deployment itself is fine, but a specific feature is broken.
        How it works: You wrap new code in an if statement controlled by a remote configuration tool (like LaunchDarkly or a custom DB flag).
        The Rollback: You don't redeploy code. You just toggle the flag to OFF in a dashboard.
                     The code stays in production but is "hidden" from the execution path.
        Benefit: Zero-second "rollback" without a deployment pipeline.

Summary Comparison:
Strategy        Speed of Rollback    Infrastructure Cost    Risk Level
Blue-Green          Instant                 High                Low
Canary              Fast                    Medium            Very Low
Rolling Update      Moderate                Low               Medium
Feature Toggle      Instant                 Low             Low (Logic based)

1. Rate Limiting (The Hard Cap):
    Rate Limiting defines how many requests a user or client can make in a specific timeframe (e.g., "100 requests per minute").
    Primary Goal: Fairness and Security.
                It prevents any single user from "hogging" all the resources or launching a Brute Force/DDoS attack.
    Behavior: Once you hit the limit, the server usually rejects the request immediately.
    Response: Typically returns an HTTP 429 Too Many Requests status code.
    Analogy: A nightclub with a "One In, One Out" policy. If the club is full, you are simply told "No" at the door.

2. Throttling (The Slowdown)
    Throttling is the process of intentionally slowing down the execution of a request to ensure the system stays stable under heavy load.
    Primary Goal: System Stability. 
            It protects the database and CPU from crashing during a sudden spike in traffic.
    Behavior: Instead of rejecting you, the server might delay your request, put it in a queue, or reduce your bandwidth.
    Response: The request eventually succeeds, but it feels "laggy" or takes longer to load.
    Analogy: An internet service provider (ISP) slowing down your connection speed after you’ve used 100GB of data, rather than cutting your internet off entirely.

Feature            Rate Limiting                           Throttling
Focus              User/Client behavior                    Server/System health
Action             Reject (HTTP 429)                       Delay/Settle/Queue
User Experience    Error Message                           Increased Latency
Duration           Usually based on fixed time windows    "Often based on current system ""stress"""
Implementation    "Token Bucket, Leaky Bucket"            "Resource monitoring, Traffic shaping"

How They Work Together:
    In a professional production environment, you usually use both:
    Rate Limiter: Sits at the API Gateway level to block abusive users immediately.
    Throttler: Sits at the Service/Database level. 
            If the database starts getting too hot, the throttler slows down incoming requests to give the DB time to breathe, 
            even if the users haven't hit their individual rate limits yet.

Common Algorithms:
    Token Bucket (Rate Limiting): You have a bucket of "tokens." 
            Each request takes one. 
            If the bucket is empty, the request is rejected.Leaky Bucket (Throttling): 
            Requests enter a bucket and "leak" out at a constant, steady rate. 
    If the bucket overflows, they are rejected, but the steady leak ensures a smooth flow to the server.

Web Adapter Pattern:
    In a Hexagonal Architecture (also known as Ports and Adapters), a Web Adapter is the entry point for your application. 
    It sits in the outermost layer and is responsible for translating HTTP requests into a format the core business logic (the "Inside") can understand.

    It essentially bridges the gap between the Web (REST, JSON, Cookies) and your Use Cases (Java Objects, Commands).

1. The Role of a Web Adapter
        A Web Adapter shouldn't contain any business logic. Its responsibilities are strictly technical:
            Mapping: Convert JSON/HTTP parameters into a "Command" or "Query" object.
            Validation: Check for basic input errors (e.g., "Email format is invalid" or "Field is missing").
            Routing: Map a specific URL and HTTP Method (GET, POST) to a specific business function.
            Response Formatting: Convert the result from the business layer back into JSON and the correct HTTP Status Code (200 OK, 201 Created, etc.).

2. Anatomy of a Web Adapter (Spring Boot)
        In Spring, your @RestController classes serve as the Web Adapters. 
        They "plug into" a Port (an interface defined in the domain layer).
            @RestController
            @RequiredArgsConstructor // Generates constructor for the final Port
            public class RegisterUserWebAdapter {
                // This is the "Inbound Port" (an Interface in your Domain layer)
                private final RegisterUserUseCase registerUserUseCase;
                @PostMapping("/v1/users")
                public ResponseEntity<UserResponse> register(@RequestBody RegisterUserRequest request) {
                    // 1. Map Web Request to a Domain Command
                    RegisterUserCommand command = new RegisterUserCommand(
                        request.getEmail(),
                        request.getPassword()
                    );
                    // 2. Call the Use Case (The "Inside" of the Hexagon)
                    User user = registerUserUseCase.register(command);
                    // 3. Map Domain Result back to a Web Response
                    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED)
                                         .body(new UserResponse(user.getId()));
                }
            }
3. Why Use This Pattern?
        If you put all your code in a Controller, your business logic becomes "married" to the Web framework.
        If you ever wanted to move from REST to a Message Queue (Kafka) or a CLI tool, you'd have to rewrite everything.
        With a Web Adapter:
            Framework Independence: Your business logic doesn't know it's being called by Spring MVC.
            Testability: You can unit test your logic without mocking complex HttpServletRequest objects.
            Clean Separation: The Web Adapter cares about HTTP codes; the Service cares about Business Rules.

Feature        Web Adapter (@RestController)        Service Layer (@Service)
Input          HTTP Request (JSON)                   Domain Objects / Commands
Logic          Formatting & Validation               Business Rules & Transactions
Output         "HTTP Response (200, 404, etc.)"      Domain Model / Entity
Dependencies   "Depends on ""Inbound Ports"""        "Depends on ""Outbound Ports"" (DB)"

Session strategy:
  In a modern distributed system (like Microservices or a multi-node cluster), managing user sessions is a critical architectural decision. 
  Since HTTP is stateless, the server needs a way to remember who the user is between requests.

  Here are the four primary session management strategies used today:
    1. Sticky Sessions (Session Affordance)
        The Load Balancer ensures that a specific user is always routed to the same server node for the duration of their session.
        How it works: The Load Balancer looks at a cookie or IP and "sticks" the user to Node A.
                     Node A stores the session in its local RAM.
        Pros: Very fast (no network calls to a database).
        Cons: Low Reliability. If Node A crashes, all users "stuck" to it lose their session data and must log in again. 
             It also makes load balancing uneven. 
    2. Session Replication
        Every node in the cluster shares session data with every other node.
        How it works: When Node A creates a session, it broadcasts that data to Node B, C, and D.
        Pros: High availability. If any node fails, any other node can pick up the request.
        Cons: Poor Scalability. As you add more nodes, the "noise" of broadcasting session updates creates massive network overhead.
    
    3. Centralized Session Store (Distributed Session)
        This is the industry standard for scalable production apps. 
        Session data is moved out of the application nodes and into a fast, external "Data Store."
        How it works: All nodes connect to a central, high-speed NoSQL database (usually Redis or Memcached).
        The Flow:
                User logs in via Node A.
                Node A saves session in Redis.
                User's next request hits Node B.
                Node B asks Redis: "Is this session valid?"
                Redis says "Yes," and Node B processes the request.
        Pros: Nodes are truly stateless. You can kill or add nodes without affecting users.
        
    4. Stateless Sessions (JWT / Token-Based)
    The server stores nothing. Instead, the session state is encrypted and sent to the client (browser).
        How it works: After login, the server sends a JSON Web Token (JWT) to the user. 
                     The user sends this token back in the header of every request.
        Pros: Maximum scalability. No database lookups needed at all.
        Cons: Security/Revocation. It is very difficult to "Log out" a user before the token expires because the server has no central record to delete.
    
    Strategy Comparison Table
    Strategy	    Storage Location	Scalability	    Reliability	    Complexity
    Sticky        	Local RAM	        Low	            Low	            Easy
    Replicated	    All Nodes	        Very Low	    High	        Medium
    Centralized	    Redis/External	    High	        High	        Medium
    Stateless	    Client (JWT)	    Extreme	        High            High (Security)

Which one should you use?
    For Monoliths: Sticky sessions are often fine for simple internal tools.
    For Enterprise/Spring Boot: Centralized Store (Redis) is the sweet spot. 
        It provides the best balance of speed and reliability.
    For Public APIs: Stateless (JWT) is preferred because it allows different services to verify users without sharing a database.

Different db on same application:
    Using multiple databases in a single Spring Boot application is a common requirement, 
    especially when you are following the CQRS pattern (e.g., using MySQL for writes and MongoDB for reads) or integrating legacy systems with new ones.

    In Spring Boot, the "Auto-configuration" magic usually handles one database perfectly.
    To use two or more, you have to manually define the configuration for each.
1. The Strategy: Manual Configuration
    When you have multiple databases, you must disable the default auto-configuration for data sources and explicitly define:
        DataSource: The connection details for each DB.
        EntityManagerFactory: To manage the entities for that specific DB.
        TransactionManager: To handle commits/rollbacks for that specific DB.
2. Configuration Steps (Step-by-Step)
    A. Define Properties
        In your application.properties, use unique prefixes for each database.
        Properties
        # Primary Database (MySQL)
        spring.datasource.primary.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/db1
        spring.datasource.primary.username=root
        spring.datasource.primary.password=pass
        # Secondary Database (PostgreSQL)
        spring.datasource.secondary.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/db2
        spring.datasource.secondary.username=user
        spring.datasource.secondary.password=pass
B. Create Configuration Classes
    You need one @Configuration class for each database. 
    You must mark one as @Primary so Spring knows which one to use by default if no specific name is provided.
        Primary Configuration:
        @Configuration
        @EnableJpaRepositories(
            basePackages = "com.app.repository.primary", // Scans only these repos
            entityManagerFactoryRef = "primaryEntityManagerFactory",
            transactionManagerRef = "primaryTransactionManager"
        )
        public class PrimaryDbConfig {
            @Primary
            @Bean
            @ConfigurationProperties("spring.datasource.primary")
            public DataSource primaryDataSource() {
                return DataSourceBuilder.create().build();
            }
            // ... define EntityManagerFactory and TransactionManager beans here
        }
3. Common Use Case Scenarios
Scenario                    Strategy
SQL + NoSQL                "Easiest: Spring Data JPA handles the SQL, and Spring Data MongoDB handles the NoSQL. 
                            They naturally use different repositories and configurations."
Two Different SQL DBs       "Medium: Requires the manual configuration shown above. 
                            You must separate your Repository interfaces into different packages (e.g., repo.mysql and repo.postgres)."
Distributed Transactions    Hard: If you save to DB1 and DB2 in the same method, a failure in DB2 won't automatically roll back DB1. 
                            You need JTA (Java Transaction API) or the Saga Pattern."
Key Challenges:
Package Scanning: You must organize your code so that entities and repositories for DB1 are in a different package than DB2. Otherwise,
                    Spring will try to map a MySQL entity to a PostgreSQL schema.
Transaction Management: By default, @Transactional only points to one Transaction Manager.
                    If you need to span both, you must specify the qualifier: @Transactional("secondaryTransactionManager").
Connection Pooling: Each DataSource creates its own connection pool (e.g., HikariCP). 
                    Monitor your memory usage, as two pools will consume twice the resources.

Multiple consumers in same application:
    To achieve high-speed parallel processing with multiple consumers in a single application, 
    your strategy depends on whether you are using Internal Messaging (within the JVM) or External Messaging (like Kafka/RabbitMQ).

    Here is how to architect for maximum throughput.
    1. The Strategy: "Competing Consumers" Pattern
        The most efficient way to achieve parallelism is the Competing Consumers pattern. 
        You have one source of data (a Queue) and multiple consumer instances (Threads or Processes) reading from it simultaneously. 
        How it works: Each message is delivered to exactly one consumer.    
        Scaling: If your processing is too slow, you simply add more consumer threads.       
    2. Implementation: Java/Spring Options
    A. Using Spring Kafka (External)
        If you are using Kafka, you achieve parallelism via Partitions.
        The Rule: One partition can only be read by one consumer in a group.
        To go faster: Increase the number of partitions in your topic and set the concurrency level in your listener.
            @KafkaListener(topics = "orders", groupId = "order-group", concurrency = "5")
            public void listen(String message) {
                // 5 separate threads will process messages in parallel
            }
    B. Using Spring Boot @Async (Internal)
        If the data is already inside your app and you just need to process it fast:
        Define a ThreadPoolTaskExecutor.
        Annotate your consumer method with @Async.
        The main thread places tasks in an internal queue, and the pool picks them up.
            @Async("taskExecutor")
            public CompletableFuture<String> processData(Data data) {
                // Parallel logic here
                return CompletableFuture.completedFuture("Done");
            }

Bottleneck            Solution
Database Contention "If 10 consumers try to update the same row, they will block each other. 
                    Use Optimistic Locking or separate your data into independent shards."
CPU Saturation       "Do not create 100 threads if you only have 8 CPU cores. 
                    The ""Context Switching"" overhead will actually make the app slower."
Shared State        "Avoid synchronized blocks or shared List objects. 
                    Use Concurrent Collections (e.g., ConcurrentHashMap) or, better yet, make your consumers completely stateless."

Advanced: The "LMAX Disruptor" Pattern
    If you need ultra-low latency (e.g., thousands of messages per millisecond), standard queues can be slow due to lock contention.
            The Disruptor uses a Ring Buffer (a circular data structure).
    It allows multiple consumers to read from the same buffer without using "locks," using a technique called CAS (Compare-And-Swap).
            This is how high-frequency trading platforms operate.

Quick Summary Checklist:
Increase Concurrency: Set your listener/thread pool size based on your CPU cores ($Cores \times 2$ is a common starting point for I/O heavy tasks).
Batching: Instead of processing 1 message at a time, have consumers take 50 messages in one go to reduce network/DB overhead.
Horizontal Scaling: If one application instance isn't enough, deploy the same application on a second node.
                    The messaging system (Kafka/Rabbit) will automatically split the work between them.

handle multiple consumers for a single REST API call to provide results as quickly as possible:
    you are likely looking for Parallel Request Aggregation (also known as the Scatter-Gather pattern).
    In this scenario, one "Orchestrator" receives the REST call, calls multiple downstream services (or data sources) at the same time, and combines the results.
1. The Strategy: Scatter-Gather (Parallelism)
    Instead of calling Service A, waiting, then calling Service B, you fire both requests simultaneously.
    Scatter: The API gateway or controller sends requests to multiple consumers/services.
    Gather: The controller waits for all responses to return, merges the data, and sends a single JSON response back to the user.
2. Implementation Options in Java
    A. CompletableFuture (Standard Java)
        This is the most common way to achieve parallel execution in a standard Spring Boot (MVC) app.
            public CompletableFuture<Response> handleRequest() {
                // Start both tasks in parallel
                CompletableFuture<User> user = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> userService.get());
                CompletableFuture<Order> orders = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> orderService.get());
            
                // Combine them when both are done
                return user.thenCombine(orders, (u, o) -> new Response(u, o));
            }
    B. Project Reactor (Spring WebFlux)
        If you want the highest performance with the least amount of memory, use WebFlux.
        It is designed specifically for this "non-blocking" parallel work.
        zip operator: It takes multiple publishers (Monos/Fluxes), waits for all of them to produce a value, and combines them.
            public Mono<Response> handleRequest() {
                Mono<User> userMono = userClient.fetchUser();
                Mono<Order> orderMono = orderClient.fetchOrders();
                return Mono.zip(userMono, orderMono)
                           .map(tuple -> new Response(tuple.getT1(), tuple.getT2()));
            }
3. Optimizing for "Quickest Result"
To truly get the result as fast as possible, implement these three "Parallel Performance" rules:
1. Fail-Fast (Timeouts)
    If you are calling 5 consumers and one is slow, your entire API call becomes slow.
    Action: Set a strict timeout (e.g., 500ms). If a consumer doesn't respond, return a partial result or an error immediately rather than making the user wait.
2. Virtual Threads (Java 21+)
    If you are on a modern Java version, use Virtual Threads. 
    They allow you to start thousands of "consumers" (threads) for parallel API calls without the massive memory overhead of traditional Platform Threads.
3. Hedged Requests
    If latency is your #1 priority, you can send the same request to two different instances of a consumer.
    Whichever one responds first is the one you use; you discard the second one. 
    This is expensive but ensures the lowest possible latency.

Method               Best For        Complexity    Performance
Sequential           Simple logic    Low            Slow
CompletableFuture    Standard Apps   Medium         Fast
WebFlux (zip)        High-scale APIs  High        Fastest (Non-blocking)
Virtual Threads      I/O Heavy tasks  Low        Very Fast

Summary Checklist for your Code:
Use a dedicated ThreadPool: Don't use the default ForkJoinPool for I/O tasks; create a custom Executor so your API calls don't starve other parts of the app.
Context Propagation: Remember that if you use Security (like JWT), you must manually pass the Security Context to the new parallel threads.
Error Handling: Use .exceptionally() or onErrorResume() to handle what happens if one consumer fails while others succeed.
